(Annie Mulligan / Freelance) Photo: Annie Mulligan, Annie Mulligan / For The Houston Chronicle Image 32 of 32 Buzz Aldrin, Clay Walker, Booker T, and Jordin Sparks fete Joanne Herring's Super Bowl extravaganza 1 / 32 Back to Gallery One could have spent all of Saturday evening at Joanne King Herring 's Extravaganza of Stars soiree and still not have seen everything.
Some 500 party-goers – that's a couple hundred more than anticipated – pulled up to Larry and Deana Blackburn 's estate on Super Bowl Eve for the event benefiting Historical Texas Treasures. From there, half-a-dozen shuttles whizzed guests through the two-acre property (boasting multiple residences) towards the main venue: a 18,000-square foot home.
"There was a full gala inside the house, and a full concert outside in the tent," Herring said.
Truthfully, music rang out both in and out of doors. A band from Houston ISD's High School for the Performing and Visual Arts put on quite a show for patrons including Elsie and Les Eckert , Elena Davis , Tracy and Harry Faulkner , Sidney and Don Faust , Rachel McNeill and Dr. Wayne Franklin , Carmina Zamarano and Rafael Chavez , and Maha and Omar Khan . Former astronaut Buzz Aldrin , the second man to walk on the moon, spent the first half of the festivities perched between an army of beauty queens. According to Herring, in attendance were 11 past and present Miss Texas title holders, eight former Miss Houstons, and a former Miss Universe, to be exact.
Attendees entering the tent received the royal treatment, too.
Scuderia Ferrari Club provided 23 exotic cars to line the walkway leading up to a literal saber arch. There, each guest was announced over a loud speaker.
The Robin King and Ernie Manouse- produced scene under the canopy did not disappoint; two open bars flanked each corner with an abundance of all-white, lounge-style seating in between. The night's honored duo, entrepreneurs Zamorano and Javaid Anwar , both shared aspirational tales of prosperity upon receiving their respective awards.
Afterwards, Aldrin, Booker T (who announced that he's running for mayor during the next election) Jordin Sparks , and Clay Walker graced the stage. Sparks and Walker each played extended sets; the country music star was slated to only perform three songs, though he wound up playing eight.
Patrons reportedly sampled Chef Eric Aldis' delectable fare or scooped up highly-coveted swag bags on the chauffeured drive back to valet; but then again, there simply wasn't enough time to experience it all.
